[ STRING TABLE — recovered from .venomq, single-byte XOR, key NOT given ]
A 19-byte run was carved out of .venomq immediately after the packed region
above. It decodes to a mutex name under single-byte XOR with some key —
exactly one key in the 0x00-0xFF range produces an all-printable result of
only uppercase letters, digits, and underscores. There is no shortcut: write
a brute-force loop (Python: `for k in range(256): ...`), try every key, and
keep the one whose decode passes that printable check.

bytes (hex):
c6 de c3 dc d2 dd d0 c6 ce dc c4 c5 d4 c9 ce a9 a9 a5 a0

[ CONFIG BLOCK — second carve, .venomq +0xC0, XOR key reused ]
Malware authors are lazy about key reuse — droppers built from the same
builder kit almost always XOR every embedded resource with the *same*
single-byte key, just to save a few bytes of code. That holds here: once
you've recovered the key from the mutex string above, reuse it on this
27-byte block. The result is plain ASCII — that's your flag, no further
decoding needed. Submit it wrapped in BV{...} or bare — either is accepted.

bytes (hex):
f4 ff e5 e3 fe e1 e8 ce f0 ff f5 ce e9 fe e3 ce f3 e3 e4 e5 f4 ce f7 fe e3 f2 f4

[ ANALYST NOTES — handoff ]
- REGION_A and REGION_B are both 1:1 byte dumps, not summaries — compute
  Shannon entropy yourself: H = -sum(p_i * log2(p_i)) over the byte-value
  histogram, p_i = count_i / total_bytes. Standard formula, any language.
  Round DOWN to the nearest whole number (0-8) before submitting — that
  keeps the answer independent of which entropy implementation you used.
- A non-standard section name plus a high-entropy region with no matching
  low-entropy "stub" of an unpacking routine nearby is a textbook static
  marker of a packed or encrypted payload (capa, Detect It Easy, and PEiD
  all flag on exactly this kind of pattern) — this is what triage looks
  like before anyone even reaches for a disassembler.
